items.name: Ext.Widget
bind
controller
defaultListenerScope
items.text:
If `true`, this component will be the default scope (this pointer) for events
specified with string names so that the scope can be dynamically resolved. The
component will automatically become the defaultListenerScope if a
{@link #cfg!controller #controller} is specified.

See the introductory docs for {@link Ext.container.Container} for some sample
usages.

**NOTE**: This value can only be reliably set at construction time. Setting it
after that time may not correctly rewire all of the potentially effected
listeners.

items.name: height
items.text:
The height of this Component; must be a valid CSS length value, e.g: `300`, `100px`, `30%`, etc.
By default, if this is not explicitly set, this Component's element will simply have its own natural size.
If set to `auto`, it will set the width to `{@link null}` meaning it will have its own natural size.

items.name: listeners
publishes
reference
items.text:
Specifies a name for this component inside its component hierarchy. This name
must be unique within its {@link Ext.container.Container#cfg!referenceHolder Ext.container.Container#referenceHolder}
or its {@link Ext.app.ViewController}. See the documentation in
{@link Ext.container.Container} for more information about references.

**Note**: Valid identifiers start with a letter or underscore and are followed
by zero or more additional letters, underscores or digits. References are case
sensitive.

items.name: session
style
items.text:
Additional CSS styles that will be rendered into an inline style attribute when
the widget is rendered.

You can pass either a string syntax:

    style: 'background:red'

Or by using an object:

    style: {
        background: 'red'
    }

When using the object syntax, you can define CSS Properties by using a string:

    style: {
        'border-left': '1px solid red'
    }

Although the object syntax is much easier to read, we suggest you to use the
string syntax for better performance.

items.name: twoWayBindable
items.text:
This object holds a map of `config` properties that will update their binding
as they are modified. For example, `value` is a key added by form fields. The
form of this config is the same as `{@link #cfg!publishes #publishes}`.

This config is defined so that updaters are not created and added for all
bound properties since most cannot be modified by the end-user and hence are
not appropriate for two-way binding.

items.name: userCls
items.text:
One or more CSS classes to add to the component's primary element. This config
is intended solely for use by the component instantiator (the "user"), not by
derived classes.

For example:

     items: [{
         xtype: 'button',
         userCls: 'my-button'
     ...
     }]

items.name: viewModel
items.text:
The `ViewModel` is a data provider for this component and its children. The
data contained in the `ViewModel` is typically used by adding `{@link #cfg!bind bind}` configs
to the components that want present or edit this data.

When set, the `ViewModel` is created and links to any inherited `{@link #cfg!viewModel viewModel}`
instance from an ancestor container as the "parent". The `ViewModel` hierarchy,
once established, only supports creation or destruction of children. The
parent of a `ViewModel` cannot be changed on the fly.

If this is a root-level `ViewModel`, the data model connection is made to this
component's associated `{@link Ext.data.Session}`. This is
determined by calling `getInheritedSession`.

items.name: width
items.text:
The width of this Component; must be a valid CSS length value, e.g: `300`, `100px`, `30%`, etc.
By default, if this is not explicitly set, this Component's element will simply have its own natural size.
If set to `auto`, it will set the width to `{@link null}` meaning it will have its own natural size.

items.name: _addDeclaredListeners
items.text: Adds declarative listeners as nested arrays of listener objects.
`true` if any listeners were added

items.name: addAfterListener
items.text: Alias for {@link #method!onAfter #onAfter}.

items.name: addBindableUpdater
items.text:
Ensures that the given property (if it is a Config System config) has a proper
"updater" method on this instance to sync changes to the config.

items.name: addDelegatedListener
items.text:
Adds a listeners with the "delegate" event option.  Users should not invoke this
method directly.  Use the "delegate" event option of
{@link Ext.util.Observable#method!addListener Ext.util.Observable#addListener} instead.

items.name: addDeprecations
items.text:
This method applies a versioned, deprecation declaration to this class. This
is typically called by the `deprecated` config.

items.name: addElementReference
items.text: Adds an element reference to this Widget instance.

items.name: name
items.text: The name of the reference

items.name: addElementReferenceOnDemand
items.text:
Reduces instantiation time for a Widget by lazily instantiating Ext.Element
references the first time they are used.  This optimization only works for elements
with no listeners specified.

items.name: name
items.text: The name of the reference

items.name: addListener
eventName
items.text:
The name of the event to listen for.
May also be an object who's property names are event names.

items.name: fn
items.text:
The method the event invokes or the *name* of
the method within the specified `scope`.  Will be called with arguments
given to {@link Ext.util.Observable#method!fireEvent Ext.util.Observable#fireEvent} plus the `options` parameter described
below.

items.name: scope
items.text:
The scope (`this` reference) in which the handler function is
executed. **If omitted, defaults to the object which fired the event.**

items.name: options
items.text:
An object containing handler configuration.

**Note:** The options object will also be passed as the last argument to every
event handler.

This object may contain any of the following properties:

items.name: scope
items.text:
The scope (`this` reference) in which the handler function is executed. **If omitted,
  defaults to the object which fired the event.**

items.name: delay
items.text:
The number of milliseconds to delay the invocation of the handler after the event
  fires.

items.name: single
items.text:
True to add a handler to handle just the next firing of the event, and then remove
  itself.

items.name: buffer
items.text:
Causes the handler to be scheduled to run in an {@link Ext.util.DelayedTask} delayed
  by the specified number of milliseconds. If the event fires again within that time,
  the original handler is _not_ invoked, but the new handler is scheduled in its place.

items.name: onFrame
items.text:
Causes the handler to be scheduled to run at the next
  {@link Ext.Function#method!requestAnimationFrame Ext.Function#requestAnimationFrame}. If the
  event fires again before that time, the handler is not rescheduled - the handler
  will only be called once when the next animation frame is fired, with the last set
  of arguments passed.

items.name: target
items.text:
Only call the handler if the event was fired on the target Observable, _not_ if the
  event was bubbled up from a child Observable.

items.name: element
delegate
items.text:
A simple selector to filter the event target or look for a descendant of the target.

  The "delegate" option is only available on Ext.dom.Element instances (or
  when attaching a listener to a Ext.dom.Element via a Component using the
  element option).

  See the *delegate* example below.

items.name: stopPropagation
items.text:
**This option is only valid for listeners bound to {@link Ext.dom.Element}.**
  `true` to call {@link Ext.event.Event#method!stopPropagation Ext.event.Event#stopPropagation} on the event object
  before firing the handler.

items.name: preventDefault
items.text:
**This option is only valid for listeners bound to {@link Ext.dom.Element}.**
  `true` to call {@link Ext.event.Event#method!preventDefault Ext.event.Event#preventDefault} on the event object
  before firing the handler.

items.name: stopEvent
items.text:
**This option is only valid for listeners bound to {@link Ext.dom.Element}.**
  `true` to call {@link Ext.event.Event#method!stopEvent Ext.event.Event#stopEvent} on the event object
  before firing the handler.

items.name: args
items.text:
Optional arguments to pass to the handler function. Any additional arguments
  passed to {@link Ext.util.Observable#method!fireEvent Ext.util.Observable#fireEvent} will be appended
  to these arguments.

items.name: destroyable
items.text:
When specified as `true`, the function returns a `destroyable` object. An object
  which implements the `{@link #method!destroy destroy}` method which removes all listeners added in this call.
  This syntax can be a helpful shortcut to using {@link #method!un #un}; particularly when
  removing multiple listeners.  *NOTE* - not compatible when using the _element_
  option.  See {@link #method!un #un} for the proper syntax for removing listeners added using the
  _element_ config.

items.name: priority
items.text:
An optional numeric priority that determines the order in which event handlers
  are run. Event handlers with no priority will be run as if they had a priority
  of 0. Handlers with a higher priority will be prioritized to run sooner than
  those with a lower priority.  Negative numbers can be used to set a priority
  lower than the default. Internally, the framework uses a range of 1000 or
  greater, and -1000 or lesser for handlers that are intended to run before or
  after all others, so it is recommended to stay within the range of -999 to 999
  when setting the priority of event handlers in application-level code.
  A priority must be an integer to be valid.  Fractional values are reserved for
  internal framework use.

items.name: order
items.text:
A legacy option that is provided for backward compatibility.
  It is recommended to use the `priority` option instead.  Available options are:

  - `'before'`: equal to a priority of `100`
  - `'current'`: equal to a priority of `0` or default priority
  - `'after'`: equal to a priority of `-100`

addManagedListener
item

items.name: clearDelegatedListeners
items.text:
Clears all listeners that were attached using the "delegate" event option.
Users should not invoke this method directly.  It is called automatically as
part of normal {@link Ext.util.Observable#method!clearListeners Ext.util.Observable#clearListeners}
processing.

items.name: clearListeners
items.text: Removes all listeners for this object including the managed listeners

items.name: clearManagedListeners
items.text: Removes all managed listeners for this object.

items.name: constructor
items.text: Creates new Object.

items.name: value
items.text: The value to wrap.

items.name: createRelayer
items.text: Creates an event handling function which re-fires the event from this object as the passed event name.

items.name: newName
items.text: The name under which to re-fire the passed parameters.

items.name: beginEnd
items.text: (optional) The caller can specify on which indices to slice.

items.name: destroy
items.text:
This method is called to cleanup an object and its resources. After calling
this method, the object should not be used any further.

items.name: doFireDelegatedEvent
items.text:
Fires a delegated event.  Users should not invoke this method directly.  It
is called automatically by the framework as needed (see the "delegate" event
option of {@link Ext.util.Observable#method!addListener Ext.util.Observable#addListener} for more
details.

items.name: doFireEvent
items.text: Continue to fire event.

items.name: enableBubble
eventNames
items.text: The event name to bubble, or an Array of event names.

items.name: fireAction
items.text:
Fires the specified event with the passed parameters and executes a function (action).
By default, the action function will be executed after any "before" event handlers
(as specified using the `order` option of
`{@link Ext.util.Observable#method!addListener Ext.util.Observable#addListener}`), but before any other
handlers are fired.  This gives the "before" handlers an opportunity to
cancel the event by returning `false`, and prevent the action function from
being called.

The action can also be configured to run after normal handlers, but before any "after"
handlers (as specified using the `order` event option) by passing `'after'`
as the `order` parameter.  This configuration gives any event handlers except
for "after" handlers the opportunity to cancel the event and prevent the action
function from being called.

items.name: eventName
items.text: The name of the event to fire.

items.name: args
items.text: Arguments to pass to handlers and to the action function.

items.name: fn
items.text: The action function.

items.name: scope
items.text:
The scope (`this` reference) in which the handler function is
executed. **If omitted, defaults to the object which fired the event.**

items.name: options
items.text:
Event options for the action function.  Accepts any
of the options of `{@link Ext.util.Observable#method!addListener Ext.util.Observable#addListener}`

items.name: order
items.text:
The order to call the action function relative
too the event handlers (`'before'` or `'after'`).  Note that this option is
simply used to sort the action function relative to the event handlers by "priority".
An order of `'before'` is equivalent to a priority of `99.5`, while an order of
`'after'` is equivalent to a priority of `-99.5`.  See the `priority` option
of `{@link Ext.util.Observable#method!addListener Ext.util.Observable#addListener}` for more details.

items.name: fireEvent
items.text:
Fires the specified event with the passed parameters (minus the event name, plus the `options` object passed
to {@link Ext.util.Observable#method!addListener Ext.util.Observable#addListener}).

An event may be set to bubble up an Observable parent hierarchy (See {@link Ext.Component#method!getBubbleTarget Ext.Component#getBubbleTarget}) by
calling {@link #method!enableBubble #enableBubble}.

items.name: eventName
items.text: The name of the event to fire.

items.name: args
items.text: Variable number of parameters are passed to handlers.
returns false if any of the handlers return false otherwise it returns true.

items.name: fireEventArgs
items.text:
Fires the specified event with the passed parameter list.

An event may be set to bubble up an Observable parent hierarchy (See {@link Ext.Component#method!getBubbleTarget Ext.Component#getBubbleTarget}) by
calling {@link #method!enableBubble #enableBubble}.

items.name: eventName
items.text: The name of the event to fire.

items.name: args
items.text: An array of parameters which are passed to handlers.
returns false if any of the handlers return false otherwise it returns true.

items.name: fireEventedAction
items.text:
Fires the specified event with the passed parameters and executes a function (action).
Evented Actions will automatically dispatch a 'before' event passing. This event will
be given a special controller that allows for pausing/resuming of the event flow.

By pausing the controller the updater and events will not run until resumed. Pausing,
however, will not stop the processing of any other before events.

items.name: eventName
items.text: The name of the event to fire.

items.name: args
items.text: Arguments to pass to handlers and to the action function.

items.name: fn
items.text: The action function.

items.name: scope
items.text:
The scope (`this` reference) in which the handler function is
executed. **If omitted, defaults to the object which fired the event.**

items.name: fnArgs
items.text:
Optional arguments for the action `fn`. If not
given, the normal `args` will be used to call `fn`. If `false` is passed, the
`args` are used but if the first argument is this instance it will be removed
from the args passed to the action function.

items.name: fixReference
items.text: Sets up a reference on our current reference holder.

items.name: getBubbleParent
items.text: Gets the bubbling parent for an Observable
The bubble parent. null is returned if no bubble target exists

items.name: getConfig
items.text:
Returns a specified config property value. If the name parameter is not passed,
all current configuration options will be returned as key value pairs.

items.name: name
items.text: The name of the config property to get.

items.name: peek
items.text: `true` to peek at the raw value without calling the getter.
The config property value.

items.name: getController
items.text:
Returns the {@link Ext.app.ViewController} instance associated with this
component via the {@link #cfg!controller #controller} config or {@link #setController} method.

Returns this component's ViewController or
null if one was not configured

items.name: getElementConfig
items.text:
A template method for modifying the {@link #property!element #element} config before it is processed.
By default adds the result of `this.getTemplate()` as the `children` array of
{@link #property!element #element} if `children` were not specified in the original
{@link #property!element #element} config.  Typically this method should not need to be implemented
in subclasses.  Instead the {@link #property!element #element} property should be use to configure
the element template for a given Widget subclass.

This method is called once when the first instance of each Widget subclass is
created.  The element config object that is returned is cached and used as the template
for all successive instances.  The scope object for this method is the class prototype,
not the instance.
the element config object

items.name: getId
items.text: Retrieves the id of this component. Will autogenerate an id if one has not already been set.
id

items.name: getInherited
items.text: This method returns an object containing the inherited properties for this instance.

items.name: inner
items.text:
Pass `true` to return `inheritedStateInner` instead
of the normal `inheritedState` object. This is only needed internally and should
not be passed by user code.
The `inheritedState` object containing inherited properties.

items.name: getInheritedConfig
items.text:
This method returns the value of a config property that may be inherited from some
ancestor.

In some cases, a config may be explicitly set on a component with the intent of
*only* being presented to its children while that component should act upon the
inherited value (see `referenceHolder` for example). In these cases the `skipThis`
parameter should be specified as `true`.

items.name: property
items.text: The name of the config property to return.

items.name: skipThis
items.text:
Pass `true` if the property should be ignored if
found on this instance. In other words, `true` means the property must be inherited
and not explicitly set on this instance.
The value of the requested `property`.

items.name: getInitialConfig
name
items.text: Name of the config option to return.

The full config object or a single config value
when `name` parameter specified.

items.name: getRefOwner
items.text:
Used by {@link Ext.ComponentQuery}, and the {@link Ext.Component#method!up Ext.Component#up}
method to find the owning Component in the linkage hierarchy.

By default this returns the Container which contains this Component.

This may be overridden by Component authors who implement ownership hierarchies
which are not based upon ownerCt, such as BoundLists being owned by Fields or Menus
being owned by Buttons.

items.name: getSize
items.text: Returns the height and width of the Component.
The current `{@link #cfg!height height}` and `{@link #cfg!width width}` of the Component.

items.name: getTdCls
items.text: Needed for when widget is rendered into a grid cell. The class to add to the cell element.

items.name: getTdType
items.text:
Partner method to {@link #method!getTdCls #getTdCls}.

Returns the base type for the component. Defaults to return `this.xtype`, but
All derived classes of {@link Ext.form.field.Text} can return the type 'textfield',
and all derived classes of {@link Ext.button.Button} can return the type 'button'

items.name: hasListener
items.text:
Checks to see if this object has any listeners for a specified event, or whether the event bubbles. The answer
indicates whether the event needs firing or not.

items.name: eventName
items.text: The name of the event to check for
`true` if the event is being listened for or bubbles, else `false`

items.name: hasOwnProperty
prop
items.text: The name of the property to test.

Returns true if object contains specified property; else
returns false.

items.name: initBindable
items.text:
This method triggers the lazy configs and must be called when it is time to
fully boot up. The configs that must be initialized are: `{@link #cfg!bind bind}`, `{@link #cfg!publishes publishes}`,
`{@link #cfg!session session}`, `{@link #cfg!twoWayBindable twoWayBindable}` and `{@link #cfg!viewModel viewModel}`.

items.name: initConfig

items.text: this

items.name: initElement
items.text:
Initializes the Element for this Widget instance.  If this is the first time a
Widget of this type has been instantiated the {@link #property!element #element} config will be
processed to create an Element.  This Element is then cached on the prototype (see
afterCachedConfig) so that future instances can obtain their element by simply
cloning the Element that was cached by the first instance.

items.name: initElementListeners
initInheritedState
items.text:
This method is called to initialize the `inheritedState` objects for this instance.
This amounts to typically copying certain properties from the instance to the given
object.

items.name: inheritedState
items.text: The state object for this instance.

items.name: inheritedStateInner
items.text: This object is only provided for containers.

items.name: invalidateInheritedState
items.text:
This method marks the current inherited state as invalid. The next time a call is
made to `{@link #method!getInherited getInherited}` the objects will be recreated and initialized.

items.name: is
items.text:
Tests whether this Widget matches a {@link Ext.ComponentQuery}
selector string.

items.name: selector
items.text: The selector string to test against.
`true` if this Widget matches the selector.

items.name: isPrototypeOf
prototype
items.text:
an object to be tested against each link in the prototype chain of the
*object* argument

items.name: object
items.text: the object whose prototype chain will be searched
Returns true if object is a prototype and false if not.

items.name: isSuspended
items.text: Checks if all events, or a specific event, is suspended.

items.name: event
items.text: The name of the specific event to check
`true` if events are suspended

items.name: isSyncing
items.text: Checks if a particular binding is synchronizing the value.

items.name: name
items.text: The name of the property being bound to.
`true` if the binding is syncing.

items.name: isXType
items.text:
Tests whether or not this Component is of a specific xtype. This can test whether this Component is descended
from the xtype (default) or whether it is directly of the xtype specified (`shallow = true`).
**If using your own subclasses, be aware that a Component must register its own xtype
to participate in determination of inherited xtypes.__

For a list of all available xtypes, see the {@link Ext.Component} header.

Example usage:

    var t = new Ext.field.Text();
    var isText = t.isXType('textfield'); // true
    var isBoxSubclass = t.isXType('field'); // true, descended from Ext.field.Field
    var isBoxInstance = t.isXType('field', true); // false, not a direct Ext.field.Field instance

items.name: xtype
items.text: The xtype to check for this Component.

items.name: shallow
items.text:
(optional) `false` to check whether this Component is descended from the xtype (this is
the default), or `true` to check whether this Component is directly of the specified xtype.
`true` if this component descends from the specified xtype, `false` otherwise.

items.name: link
items.text:
Adds a "destroyable" object to an internal list of objects that will be destroyed
when this instance is destroyed (via `{@link #method!destroy #destroy}`).
The `value` passed.

items.name: lookupController
items.text:
Gets the controller that controls this view. May be a controller that belongs
to a view higher in the hierarchy.

items.name: skipThis
items.text:
`true` to not consider the controller directly attached
to this view (if it exists).
The controller. `{@link null}` if no controller is found.

items.name: lookupReferenceHolder
items.text: Gets the Controller or Component that is used as the reference holder for this view.

items.name: skipThis
items.text:
`false` to return this as the reference holder if
this instance has set `referenceHolder`. Unlike `{@link #method!getInheritedConfig getInheritedConfig}` this method
defaults to `true` because it is possible that a `{@link #cfg!reference reference}` property set by the
owner of a component that is also a `referenceHolder` itself. In this case, the
`{@link #cfg!reference reference}` connects not to this component but to the parent referenceHolder.
The reference holder.

items.name: lookupSession
items.text:
Returns the `{@link Ext.data.Session}` for this instance. This property may come
from this instance's `{@link #cfg!session #session}` or be inherited from this object's parent.

items.name: skipThis
items.text:
Pass `true` to ignore a `{@link #cfg!session session}` configured on
this instance and only consider an inherited session.

items.name: lookupViewModel
items.text:
Returns the `{@link Ext.app.ViewModel}` for this instance. This property may come from this
this instance's `{@link #cfg!viewModel #viewModel}` or be inherited from this object's parent.

items.name: skipThis
items.text:
Pass `true` to ignore a `{@link #cfg!viewModel viewModel}` configured on
this instance and only consider an inherited view model.

items.name: makeBindableUpdater
items.text:
Returns an `update` method for the given Config that will call `{@link #method!publishState #publishState}`
to ensure two-way bindings (via `{@link #cfg!bind bind}`) as well as any `{@link #cfg!publishes publishes}` are updated.
This method is cached on the `cfg` instance for re-use.
The updater function.

items.name: mon
items.text: Shorthand for {@link #method!addManagedListener #addManagedListener}.

items.name: mun
items.text: Shorthand for {@link #method!removeManagedListener #removeManagedListener}.

items.name: onAfter
items.text:
Appends an after-event handler.

Same as {@link Ext.util.Observable#method!addListener Ext.util.Observable#addListener} with `order` set
to `'after'`.

items.name: eventName
items.text: The name of the event to listen for.

items.name: fn
items.text: The method the event invokes.

items.name: scope
items.text: The scope for `fn`.

items.name: options
items.text: An object containing handler configuration.

items.name: onBefore
items.text:
Appends a before-event handler.  Returning `false` from the handler will stop the event.

Same as {@link Ext.util.Observable#method!addListener Ext.util.Observable#addListener} with `order` set
to `'before'`.

items.name: eventName
items.text: The name of the event to listen for.

items.name: fn
items.text: The method the event invokes.

items.name: scope
items.text: The scope for `fn`.

items.name: options
items.text: An object containing handler configuration.

items.name: onInheritedAdd

items.name: relayEvents
items.text:
Relays selected events from the specified Observable as if the events were fired by `this`.

For example if you are extending Grid, you might decide to forward some events from store.
So you can do this inside your initComponent:

    this.relayEvents(this.getStore(), ['load']);

The grid instance will then have an observable 'load' event which will be passed
the parameters of the store's load event and any function fired with the grid's
load event would have access to the grid using the this keyword (unless the event
is handled by a controller's control/listen event listener in which case 'this'
will be the controller rather than the grid).

items.name: events
items.text:
Array of event names to relay or an Object with key/value
pairs translating to ActualEventName/NewEventName respectively. For example:
    this.relayEvents(this, {add:'push', remove:'pop'});

Would now redispatch the add event of this as a push event and the remove event as a pop event.

items.name: valueOf
items.text:
Returns the primitive value of the specified object.

JavaScript calls the `{@link #method!valueOf valueOf}` method to convert an object to a primitive value. You rarely need to
invoke the `{@link #method!valueOf valueOf}` method yourself; JavaScript automatically invokes it when encountering an
object where a primitive value is expected.

By default, the `{@link #method!valueOf valueOf}` method is inherited by every object descended from `{@link Object}`. Every built-
in core object overrides this method to return an appropriate value. If an object has no primitive
value, `{@link #method!valueOf valueOf}` returns the object itself, which is displayed as:

    [object Object]

You can use `{@link #method!valueOf valueOf}` within your own code to convert a built-in object into a primitive value.
When you create a custom object, you can override `Object.valueOf` to call a custom method instead
of the default `{@link Object}` method.

You can create a function to be called in place of the default `{@link #method!valueOf valueOf}` method. Your function must
take no arguments.

Suppose you have an object type `myNumberType` and you want to create a `{@link #method!valueOf valueOf}` method for it.
The following code assigns a user-defined function to the object's valueOf method:

    myNumberType.prototype.valueOf = new Function(functionText)

With the preceding code in place, any time an object of type `myNumberType` is used in a context
where it is to be represented as a primitive value, JavaScript automatically calls the function
defined in the preceding code.

An object's `{@link #method!valueOf valueOf}` method is usually invoked by JavaScript, but you can invoke it yourself as
follows:

    myNumber.valueOf()

Note: Objects in string contexts convert via the `{@link #method!toString toString}` method, which is different from
`{@link String}` objects converting to string primitives using `{@link #method!valueOf valueOf}`. All objects have a string
conversion, if only `"[object type]"`. But many objects do not convert to number, boolean, or
function.
Returns value of the object or the object itself.

items.name: $configPrefixed
items.text:
The value `true` causes `config` values to be stored on instances using a
property name prefixed with an underscore ("_") character. A value of `false`
stores `config` values as properties using their exact name (no prefix).

items.name: $configStrict
items.text:
The value `true` instructs the `{@link #method!initConfig initConfig}` method to only honor values for
properties declared in the `config` block of a class. When `false`, properties
that are not declared in a `config` block will be placed on the instance.

defaultBindProperty
items.text:
This property is used to determine the property of a `{@link #cfg!bind bind}` config that is just
the value. For example, if `defaultBindProperty="value"`, then this shorthand
`{@link #cfg!bind bind}` config:

     bind: '{name}'

Is equivalent to this object form:

     bind: {
         value: '{name}'
     }

The `{@link #property!defaultBindProperty defaultBindProperty}` is set to "value" for form fields and to "store" for
grids and trees.

items.name: hasListeners
items.text:
This object holds a key for any event that has a listener. The listener may be set
directly on the instance, or on its class or a super class (via {@link #observe}) or
on the {@link Ext.app.EventBus}. The values of this object are truthy
(a non-zero number) and falsy (0 or undefined). They do not represent an exact count
of listeners. The value for an event is truthy if the event must be fired and is
falsy if there is no need to fire the event.

The intended use of this property is to avoid the expense of fireEvent calls when
there are no listeners. This can be particularly helpful when one would otherwise
have to call fireEvent hundreds or thousands of times. It is used like this:

     if (this.hasListeners.foo) {
         this.fireEvent('foo', this, arg1);
     }
